rt IV. The Filipino Body in Time and Space -- t11. Pinoy Posteriority -- t12. The Case of Felicidad Ocampo: A Palimpsest of Transpacific Feminism -- t13. Hair Lines: Filipino American Art and the Uses of Abstraction -- t14. Eartha Kitt’s “Waray Waray”: The Filipina in Black Feminist Performance Imaginary -- tPart V. Philippine Cultures at Large: Homing in on Global Filipinos and Their Discontents -- t15. Diasporic and Liminal Subjectivities in the Age of Empire: “Beyond Biculturalism” in the Case of the Two Ongs -- t16. The Legacy of Undesirability: Filipino TNTs, “Irregular Migrants,” and “Outlaws” in the US Cultural Imaginary -- t17. “Home” and The Filipino Channel: Stabilizing Economic Security, Migration Patterns, and Diaspora through New Technologies -- t18. “Come Back Home Soon”: The Pleasures and Agonies of “Homeland” Visits -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter years of occupying a vexed position in the American academy, Philippine studies has come into its own, emerging as a trenchant and dynamic space of inquiry. Filipino Studies is a field-defining collection of vibrant voices, critical perspectives, and provocative ideas about the cultural, political, and economic state of the Philippines and its diaspora. Traversing issues of colonialism, neoliberalism, globalization, and nationalism, this volume examines not only the past and present position of the Philippines and its people, but also advances new frameworks for re-conceptualizing this growing field. Written by a prestigious lineup of international scholars grappling with the legacies of colonialism and imperial power, the essays examine both the genealogy of the Philippines’ hyphenated identity as well as the future trajectory of the field. Hailing from multiple disciplines in the humanities and social sciences, the contributors revisit and contest traditional renditions of Philippine colonial histories, from racial formations and the Japanese occupation to the Cold War and “independence” from the United States. Whether addressing the contested memories of World War II, the “voyage” of Filipino men and women into the U.S. metropole, or migrant labor and the notion of home, the assembled essays tease out the links between the past and present, with a hopeful longing for various futures. Filipino Studies makes bold declarations about the productive frameworks that open up new archives and innovative landscapes of knowledge for Filipino and Filipino American Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Asian / General.2bisacsh1 aAlidio, Kimberly, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBascara, Victor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenitez, Francisco, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlanco, John D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBonus, Rick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurns, Lucy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChu, Richard T., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCruz, Denise, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDiaz, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspiritu, Augusto F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEspiritu, Augusto, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFajardo, Kale Bantigue, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGo, Julian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuevarra, Anna Romina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular